vectorData.altText: 13. Which of the following contain sensory fibres that carry information regarding tissue damage (ultimately interpreted as pain) from the esophagus toward the central nervous system? Choose all that apply.
That's right!  These options correctly trace the pathway of visceral sensory fibres conducting pain afferents from the esophagus to the spinal cord.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Viscera are innervated by sensory fibres, as well as sympathetic and parasympathetic motor fibres. As in somatic nerves, visceral nerves contain both sensory and motor fibres.
Some sensory fibres travel with the parasympathetics, back along the vagus nerve to their origin in the brainstem. These sensory fibres carry homeostatic information, such as blood gas and blood pressure.
Other sensory fibres travel with the sympathetics, back along the cardiac, esophageal or pulmonary splanchnic nerves, back to their origin in the upper thoracic spinal cord levels. These sensory fibres carry information regarding tissue damage due to inflammation, ischemia     and undue stretch, which the CNS interprets as pain.
Lack of blood supply; this is the basis of angina pectoris or cardiac pain, as occurs with occlusion of coronary arteries.
